{"add":{"doc":{"id":"fad11bf79abac79ae9700d84620050cbc32e66af5de60cb2c96bb92e4a6fb63a","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/89/JohnKnox.jpg/180px-JohnKnox.jpg","previous":[],"after":["When Mary Tudor ascended the throne and reestablished Roman Catholicism, Knox was forced to resign his position and leave the country. Knox first moved to Geneva and then to Frankfurt. On his return to Scotland, he led the Protestant Reformation in Scotland, in partnership with the Scottish Protestant nobility. Knox helped write the new confession of faith and the ecclesiastical order for the newly created reformed church, the Kirk. He continued to serve as the religious leader of the Protestants throughout Mary's reign. In several interviews with the queen, Knox admonished her for supporting Roman practices. Eventually, when she was imprisoned and James VI enthroned in her stead, he openly attacked her in sermons. He continued to preach until his final days."]}}}